Safe zones.

A safe zone is a sanctuary the player can duck into where enemies can't follow and their shots can't reach. Enemies treat the zone as a solid wall they're unable to step into, and projectiles flying toward it are stopped at its edge. It's the entity for a guarded doorway, a panic room, a checkpoint alcove — anywhere the player should be able to stop, catch their breath, and be untouchable for a moment.

How a safe zone works.

The zone covers a rectangular area. While it's there:

Enemies cannot enter it. When an NPC's next step would carry it into the zone, it's blocked at the boundary exactly as if the zone were a wall, so pursuers pile up at the edge and can't reach the player inside.
Projectiles cannot pass into it. A bullet, arrow, or thrown weapon heading into the zone is stopped at its edge rather than flying through to hit the player.

The player moves freely in and out. Crossing the boundary inward plays the zone's entry cue, and crossing back out plays its exit cue, so the player always hears when they've stepped into safety and when they've left it. Note that the zone keeps enemies and their fire out — it doesn't heal the player or stop hazards that are already inside the area, so place it on genuinely empty ground.

Safe zone fields.

The safe zone form takes the following:

Coordinates. A minimum and maximum x and y (and a minimum and maximum z on 3d maps), marking the protected rectangle.

Safe sound (a folder name from the safe sounds list, or none). The audio theme; the bundle supplies an in clip (played when the player enters) and an out clip (played when the player leaves). Pick none for a silent zone.

Auditioning sounds in the builder.

While the safe sound list is focused in the form, press space to hear the out clip of the highlighted theme and hold control and press L to hear its in clip.

Authoring safe zones by hand.

If you edit main.sif directly, a safe zone is: safe_zone minx maxx miny maxy safetype. On 3d maps a minimum and maximum z follow the y pair: safe_zone minx maxx miny maxy minz maxz safetype. The safe sound must match a safe sounds folder name or the word none.
